holds himselfe miserable, &amp; would confesse it to thee if his ambition did not stay him: and if he feared not by this confession to make himself contemptible, the which he most abhorreth, he would shew thee, that in his greatest banquets, he hath no more assurance thē he, ouer whose head there hangs a naked sword, staied onely by a horse haire, as in old time that of the Tyrant of Sicile. But the aduertisement giuen to Philip King of Macedon growne insolent for the victory of Cheronee, by Archidamus King of Sparta, after the Spartane manner, is notable: Philip, said hee, measure thy shaddow, if thou findest it bigger then of custome: as if hee would say, Why doest thou

