               The 2. is taken from religion, and from the homage which man doth owe vnto God for the immortality of his soule; not in one Country but in all; not in one age, but for euer; not in one person, but generally in all by some adoration, prayer, of sacrifice, in what fashion soeuer, man will sooner forget his King, his father, yea himselfe, then his God; yet hee makes no doubt but there is a King, he sees him, he knowes him, he honours him: and that he hath a father, of whom hee holds his life, and with whom he doth conuerse dayly, and whom he is bound to loue; finally, he tries himselfe,

